A wise LLM once told me:

The root cause here is that you’re actually caching two layers of “ParquetFile” objects:
    1.    in your class-level _parquet_cache
    2.    in your @lru_cache-decorated _get_parquet_file

On the very first create(...) run, both caches get populated with live file handles.  When that loader instance is eventually destroyed, your __del__ closes all of those handles.

On the second call to create(...), your _get_parquet sees the closed handle in _parquet_cache, pops it, and goes looking for a fresh one… but then it calls _get_parquet_file(...), which is still decorated with @lru_cache, so it immediately returns the same already-closed ParquetFile that was cached on the first run.  Hence: “Parquet file is closed” every time thereafter.
